:: Fundamental Experience {"position":"750,1100","size":"200,100"}
Before I started in software, I had a lot of different roles. Starting with mowing lawns, which showed me the value of a good day's work.

After that I worked in a deli, which taught me the value of teamwork, good customer service, and respect for people who work in food service.

Then I moved to working in a garden center -- because I genuinely have a passion for plants -- which taught me how to learn on the job quickly and effectively.

Following that, I worked as an appliance delivery hand, then support driver, then delivery driver, then delivery driver lead and trainer. All of those roles taught me communication and balance.

I was an epoxy countertop installer, which showed me that sometimes crazy attention to detail is the whole job.

I was a Solar Lead Setter, which taught me resilience and verbal communication skills.

And finally, I was a logistics coordinator for a Kona Ice, which taught me work-life balance and just how critical that really is.

It was quite a ride -- and even though every one of those jobs taught me something, I love what I do today even more because of all of them. Now that I'm in a career where I get to use my mind to the fullest, I'm extremely happy not to be relying solely on my physical abilities.

