:: Rules of Coding {"position":"1250,1350","size":"200,100"}
I subscribe to the idea that every line of code is both an asset and a liability. Statistically, the fewer lines of code, the fewer lines that can break.

The shortest distance between two points is a straight line -- simple, effective, adaptable. I call it ruthless simplicity. Where it gets controversial is when that comes at the cost of DRY code, but I think those two ideas can coexist if you're intentional about it.

"No comments" is another one of mine. If you can't read the code from the variable names and context alone, your code is likely too complicated.

I'm not interested in over-engineering something just to make it look impressive. If there's a simpler way to do it that's solid, readable, and maintainable, that's usually the better call.

